00:38:59.490 --> 00:39:04.160
in the accuracy of GPS or issues
for long-range communications.

00:39:04.160 --> 00:39:07.690
Ultimately, the big effect, I
think, would be on satellites

00:39:07.690 --> 00:39:09.580
that happen to be
in low Earth orbit.

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:12.620
If the densities get high
enough, it can cause charging

00:39:12.620 --> 00:39:15.360
on the spacecraft, which I
don't think would damage it,

00:39:15.360 --> 00:39:16.660
but could affect instruments

00:39:16.660 --> 00:39:18.940
and the measurements
on those satellites.

00:39:18.940 --> 00:39:21.790
I think that would be the
main effect in that case.

00:39:24.270 --> 00:39:27.340
&gt;&gt; What is the relationship, if
there is one, between airglow

00:39:27.340 --> 00:39:29.260
and the aurora borealis?

00:39:29.260 --> 00:39:30.560
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: Sure.

00:39:30.560 --> 00:39:32.600
Thank you, and I forgot
to repeat your question.

00:39:32.600 --> 00:39:35.230
You were asking about
what would the effect

00:39:35.230 --> 00:39:39.780
of the El Nino density in
the ionosphere have down here

00:39:39.780 --> 00:39:43.210
on Earth, but your question
was: How are the aurora

00:39:43.210 --> 00:39:44.510
and the airglow related?

00:39:44.510 --> 00:39:45.810
Is that right?

00:39:45.810 --> 00:39:48.530
Okay. Yeah, they are
related, actually,

00:39:48.530 --> 00:39:54.330
because they're both very
similar chemical processes.

00:39:54.330 --> 00:39:58.870
So the aurora happens when the
sun is giving off this steady

00:39:58.870 --> 00:40:00.170
solar wind --

00:40:00.170 --> 00:40:03.760
-- and magnetic field which
then impacts on the Earth.

00:40:03.760 --> 00:40:06.200
Some of those particles leak

00:40:06.200 --> 00:40:10.610
into the Earth's magnetic field
area and kind of get stuck there

00:40:10.610 --> 00:40:15.120
and hang out there, and then
ionospheric particles also kind

00:40:15.120 --> 00:40:17.950
of leak upward into that region,

00:40:17.950 --> 00:40:21.180
and then during some
geomagnetic events,

00:40:21.180 --> 00:40:24.450
like coronal mass ejections,
they can get accelerated

00:40:24.450 --> 00:40:27.820
in a way that causes them to
cruise down the field lines,

00:40:27.820 --> 00:40:29.930
kind of like in that
ionosphere video.

00:40:29.930 --> 00:40:33.360
That's why you get the aurora in
a ring, because it's particles

00:40:33.360 --> 00:40:36.230
that are traveling down
field lines from a region

00:40:36.230 --> 00:40:38.770
where they got accelerated.

00:40:38.770 --> 00:40:43.910
But what causes the line is
those particles coming down.

00:40:43.910 --> 00:40:47.550
They impact the atmosphere,
knock electrons off

00:40:47.550 --> 00:40:49.250
of the particles there.

00:40:49.250 --> 00:40:53.170
That causes them sometimes to
give off light immediately.

00:40:53.170 --> 00:40:56.510
Other times, you
get other light also

00:40:56.510 --> 00:40:59.380
from when the particles
recombine,

00:40:59.380 --> 00:41:02.410
and certain chemical
interactions give off certain

00:41:02.410 --> 00:41:03.710
types of light.

00:41:03.710 --> 00:41:05.510
So that's how it
works in the aurora.

00:41:05.510 --> 00:41:07.560
In the airglow, it's
almost the same thing.

00:41:07.560 --> 00:41:09.860
It's just sunlight
causing it to happen,

00:41:09.860 --> 00:41:13.230
and so you also get
excitation, they call it,

00:41:13.230 --> 00:41:14.980
where you get this
immediate release of light,

00:41:14.980 --> 00:41:17.350
and then you also
get recombination,

00:41:17.350 --> 00:41:20.580
especially at night, when
you're not getting bombarded

00:41:20.580 --> 00:41:21.880
with sunlight anymore.

00:41:21.880 --> 00:41:24.280
Those electrons and ions
kind of find their way back

00:41:24.280 --> 00:41:26.170
to each other, and some of them

00:41:26.170 --> 00:41:27.970
when they recombine
will give off light

00:41:27.970 --> 00:41:29.770
in a variety of different
colors.

00:41:29.770 --> 00:41:32.950
So it's very similar.

