00:42:57.480 --> 00:42:59.910
or so many feet per
minute or miles per hour?

00:42:59.910 --> 00:43:03.620
And then of course, you
know, space is zero.

00:43:03.620 --> 00:43:05.720
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: Yeah,
so essentially,

00:43:05.720 --> 00:43:08.360
getting out of the
Earth's atmosphere depends

00:43:08.360 --> 00:43:11.080
on reaching an escape
velocity, right,

00:43:11.080 --> 00:43:14.570
so that your velocity
is actually faster

00:43:14.570 --> 00:43:18.160
than gravity can pull you down
toward the Earth, essentially,

00:43:18.160 --> 00:43:20.370
to keep you up out of there.

00:43:20.370 --> 00:43:24.100
In terms of -- and the question
was about the atmosphere

00:43:24.100 --> 00:43:28.530
as it becomes space and
that boundary there.

00:43:28.530 --> 00:43:32.590
Is there a defining point
where the particles stop moving

00:43:32.590 --> 00:43:34.000
with the Earth, essentially?

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:39.670
Yeah, I think that
the answer would be

00:43:39.670 --> 00:43:44.020
that the particles
fall off gradually,

00:43:44.020 --> 00:43:49.240
and where the point is that
they become space I think is

00:43:49.240 --> 00:43:51.510
something that we
haven't really measured.

00:43:51.510 --> 00:43:53.340
I'm not sure if they're --

00:43:53.340 --> 00:43:55.240
they're probably our
models that would say,

00:43:55.240 --> 00:43:58.220
but that actually would
be dependent a little bit

00:43:58.220 --> 00:44:01.130
on the expansion of
the atmosphere due

00:44:01.130 --> 00:44:04.640
to the energy coming
from the sun.

00:44:04.640 --> 00:44:05.940
&gt;&gt; And a follow-up.

00:44:05.940 --> 00:44:07.890
Is there any stripping
of our atmosphere

00:44:07.890 --> 00:44:10.550
over the course,
ever, at any point?

00:44:10.550 --> 00:44:13.690
I know with ozone, the hole
in the ozone at some point,

00:44:13.690 --> 00:44:16.010
but is there stripping
because of that movement?

00:44:16.010 --> 00:44:17.310
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: Yeah.

00:44:17.310 --> 00:44:18.610
The question is: Is there a sort

00:44:18.610 --> 00:44:19.910
of stripping effect
of the atmosphere?

00:44:19.910 --> 00:44:23.470
And I think that's a really
great and interesting question,

00:44:23.470 --> 00:44:26.690
because I think on other
planets in our solar system,

00:44:26.690 --> 00:44:28.150
that's the understanding, right,

00:44:28.150 --> 00:44:31.520
is that they may have had
atmospheres in the past

00:44:31.520 --> 00:44:33.280
that were stripped away.

00:44:33.280 --> 00:44:35.680
This is not my area
of expertise at all,

00:44:35.680 --> 00:44:40.890
but I am really interested in
it, and I think that the idea is

00:44:40.890 --> 00:44:43.000
that certain types of gas
could have been stripped away

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:46.590
in the past, but you'd have
to ask someone more expert

00:44:46.590 --> 00:44:48.430
than me, but thank you.

00:44:48.430 --> 00:44:53.080
&gt;&gt; On the slide up there,
it says the satellite

00:44:53.080 --> 00:44:58.500
and the rocket on June 6th were
in California, and on June 14th,

00:44:58.500 --> 00:45:01.290
they're going to be
up in the Pacific.

00:45:01.290 --> 00:45:02.930
How do you get the
rocket up there?

00:45:02.930 --> 00:45:05.000
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: Yeah, and thank
you for pointing this out,

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:07.470
because I poorly made
this slide, actually.

00:45:07.470 --> 00:45:08.770
&gt;&gt; June 6th was yesterday.

00:45:08.770 --> 00:45:13.620
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: This picture
is from May 22nd, 2018.

00:45:13.620 --> 00:45:15.470
At that point, the satellite

00:45:15.470 --> 00:45:18.400
and the rocket were
all in California.

00:45:18.400 --> 00:45:22.280
Yesterday they did their
mission readiness review,

00:45:22.280 --> 00:45:25.770
and I don't know when it
happens, to be honest,

00:45:25.770 --> 00:45:30.880
but I do know that what happens
is that they take the rocket,

00:45:30.880 --> 00:45:33.830
and the satellite, and
everything all put together.

00:45:33.830 --> 00:45:38.170
They ferry it out to the
Marshall Islands shortly before

00:45:38.170 --> 00:45:39.820
launch on June 14th.

00:45:39.820 --> 00:45:41.550
&gt;&gt; On a ship?

00:45:41.550 --> 00:45:44.750
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: I
think so, yeah.

00:45:44.750 --> 00:45:46.900
&gt;&gt; Stephanie Marcus: I was
also interested in that,

00:45:46.900 --> 00:45:51.460
in the type of launch where
it's going to be an airplane

00:45:51.460 --> 00:45:53.700
with the rocket and
the satellite.

00:45:53.700 --> 00:45:55.380
Why do they use the airplane?

00:45:55.380 --> 00:45:57.330
Normally they would just
use the rocket for that.

00:45:57.330 --> 00:45:59.300
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: That's
right, I think, and again,

00:45:59.300 --> 00:46:04.630
it's not my expertise why
ICON is being launched

00:46:04.630 --> 00:46:08.260
on this Pegasus rocket which
launches from an airplane.

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:10.700
They actually take off
with the airplane first.

00:46:10.700 --> 00:46:12.700
But I believe it's because
you need less thrust

00:46:12.700 --> 00:46:15.220
and propulsion once
you're already in the air

00:46:15.220 --> 00:46:17.990
above the densest part
of the atmosphere,

00:46:17.990 --> 00:46:23.590
and so that makes it easier
to get it up into orbit.

00:46:23.590 --> 00:46:24.890
&gt;&gt; Stephanie Marcus: Okay.

00:46:24.890 --> 00:46:27.190
That should be interesting.

00:46:28.550 --> 00:46:30.520
&gt;&gt; What's the benefit from
launching it all the way

00:46:30.520 --> 00:46:33.770
out in the Pacific versus
Vandenberg or anywhere else?

00:46:33.770 --> 00:46:35.070
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: I know it was --

00:46:35.070 --> 00:46:36.530
&gt;&gt; Stephanie Marcus: Question.

00:46:36.530 --> 00:46:38.340
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: -- something
that had to be discussed.

00:46:38.340 --> 00:46:42.860
Why would you choose to launch
from Marshall Islands instead

00:46:42.860 --> 00:46:47.880
of somewhere like
Vandenberg or Kennedy?

00:46:47.880 --> 00:46:50.270
I believe that the reason was

00:46:50.270 --> 00:46:54.660
because the Marshall Islands
gave them the inclination

00:46:54.660 --> 00:46:56.220
that they wanted for the orbit.

00:46:56.220 --> 00:47:01.230
So it's something like a 20 or
22-degree inclination orbit,

00:47:01.230 --> 00:47:04.000
which allows it to get
up around the tropics

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:07.070
and also measure
near the equator.

00:47:07.070 --> 00:47:09.480
I think that was the reason.

00:47:11.550 --> 00:47:13.850
&gt;&gt; Wasn't it fairly recently
that the charged particles

00:47:13.850 --> 00:47:16.010
in the airglow were
photographed,

00:47:16.010 --> 00:47:19.930
like within the past
20 years or something?

00:47:19.930 --> 00:47:21.720
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: So the question
is, "How long has it been

00:47:21.720 --> 00:47:24.030
since we started measuring
the charged particles

00:47:24.030 --> 00:47:25.330
in the airglow?"

00:47:25.330 --> 00:47:26.840
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I just remember
seeing like a photograph.

00:47:26.840 --> 00:47:30.140
It was like a discovery, and
everybody was excited about it.

00:47:30.140 --> 00:47:31.440
&gt;&gt; Sarah Jones: Oh, yeah.

00:47:31.440 --> 00:47:32.740
I think I know what you mean.

00:47:32.740 --> 00:47:36.360
One of the satellites that was
able to measure the aurora,

00:47:36.360 --> 00:47:39.780
both regions and all
of the airglow at once.

00:47:39.780 --> 00:47:41.080
It was the first time.

00:47:41.080 --> 00:47:43.340
It was done very recently.

00:47:43.340 --> 00:47:44.640
I'm sorry.

00:47:44.640 --> 00:47:46.070
I don't remember what
mission that was, but in terms

00:47:46.070 --> 00:47:48.300
of just measuring the airglow,

00:47:48.300 --> 00:47:50.390
it's actually been
something that's been done

00:47:50.390 --> 00:47:53.810
since the beginning of
this research field.

00:47:53.810 --> 00:47:55.290
Also measuring the aurora.

00:47:55.290 --> 00:47:57.440
And it's an interesting
question,

00:47:57.440 --> 00:48:00.020
because we can use
the upper atmosphere

00:48:00.020 --> 00:48:02.460
as a real laboratory
for chemistry.

00:48:02.460 --> 00:48:05.860
Actually, there were chemical
emissions in the aurora

00:48:05.860 --> 00:48:08.740
and airglow that had
never been seen on Earth,

00:48:08.740 --> 00:48:11.740
and so there were big
debates about, "What is this?

00:48:11.740 --> 00:48:13.280
What is the light coming from?"

00:48:13.280 --> 00:48:15.080
We know it's coming
from a chemical reaction

00:48:15.080 --> 00:48:18.630
between the particles, but
there were even speculations

00:48:18.630 --> 00:48:21.460
about new elements
in the periodic table

00:48:21.460 --> 00:48:25.540
that might give off this kind
of light, and the reason was

00:48:25.540 --> 00:48:29.690
because some of these lines come
from metastable states, which,

00:48:29.690 --> 00:48:33.160
at least at that time
and the level of vacuum

00:48:33.160 --> 00:48:36.240
that they could achieve in
their laboratory experiments,

00:48:36.240 --> 00:48:38.450
they would never see in the lab.

00:48:38.450 --> 00:48:43.430
So the red line that happens
in the aurora and the airglow,

00:48:43.430 --> 00:48:48.950
the particle receives the energy
and just kind of is metastable,

00:48:48.950 --> 00:48:52.810
so it hangs out for like an
entire minute before giving off

00:48:52.810 --> 00:48:56.250
light, and unless you're
at a really low density,

00:48:56.250 --> 00:48:58.150
before that minute is up,
you're going to get hit

00:48:58.150 --> 00:49:00.910
by some other particle, and
it's going to lose energy

00:49:00.910 --> 00:49:03.330
that way instead of
giving off the red light.

00:49:03.330 --> 00:49:06.980
So yeah, it's been
this really great way

00:49:06.980 --> 00:49:10.480
of studying basic chemistry.

